content:
Human-Labeled Majority-voted Examples:
Example 1:
Text: It would be better to have this discussion on the TKD talk page. Why don't you re-post it there?
Annotation: 14

Example 2:
Text: No, I didn't know that. Where does this "rule" come from?
Annotation: 9

Example 3:
Text: The article <url> (written with two s) was rightly deleted as it contained almost no content (Timothy (Tim) Ferriss is the author of The 4-Hour Workweek). I think you mean the science-fiction writer <url> (written wit one s) ?
Annotation: 13

Example 4:
Text: When someone tags articles using non-existent criteria, there's no way the articles should be deleted. The deleting admin has restored Reviewmageddon now, so it seems it's sorted out?
Annotation: 13

Example 5:
Text: <url> and <url> seem to be two articles on the same subject.  What's the point of having separate articles?
Annotation: 7

Example 6:
Text: Your comments have been extremely helpful. I'd like to put this FAC to bed soon; is there any chance that you might be able to finish off your review of the article this weekend?
Annotation: 16

Example 7:
Text: Done. Comments?
Annotation: 12

Example 8:
Text: I'm sorry, but I'm unlikely to have time to help. Maybe try <url>?
Annotation: 15

Example 9:
Text: Hello, sorry I probably should have asked first, but I thought it might be a good idea to nominate one of the images you uploaded, <url>, for featured picture. I hope you don't mind me taking the liberty, as it were?
Annotation: 16

Example 10:
Text: I deleted the redirects <url> and <url> that were a result of the page moves.  Is that all you needed?
Annotation: 10
Imputed Majority-voted Examples:
Example 1:
Text: Good work maintaining the Tibet page i seems to getting an increasing amount of traffic!!! Is our Chinese friend still persisting?
Annotation: 12

Example 2:
Text: I noticed you put "NB" and then the credit for the original picture that I cropped. What does "NB" stand for?
Annotation: 12

Example 3:
Text: Need help with EF 175 via email. Mind <url> so we can discuss?
Annotation: 12

Example 4:
Text: The template I want is the one that goes at the bottom of the article and produces a message that goes something like 'This article is a copy of the (X) article in the German wikipedia, version 21 December 2009 10:04.' What is that template?
Annotation: 12

Example 5:
Text: I'm pretty sure there already is a filter (possibly more than one) for this. What page got moved?
Annotation: 12

Example 6:
Text: Third, what picture then should go into the Harrison Ford infobox?  Would this one (Image:Harrison Ford 1) do it?
Annotation: 12

Example 7:
Text: Thankyou for the message. Isn't it academic convention to specify which edition one has cited and give the page numbers therefrom?
Annotation: 15

Example 8:
Text: <url> is kindxe1 related to the subjects we have been dealing with. Would you mind if I ask you for advice?
Annotation: 12

Example 9:
Text: Are the remaining IPs on <url> still a problem? If so is Tom dealing with it?
Annotation: 12

Example 10:
Text: Okay. Meanwhile, can you think of a good line for a <url> submission?
Annotation: 16
Predict the integer label of the following example:
Text: Thanks. As for the previous edits, should I make a note on the User Page that it's my account?
Annotation:
If you output anything other than a single integer (and absolutely nothing else, including explanatory text), your output will invalidate the dataset. So, please only output a single integer.
